{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17536922","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17536922"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T17:11:21+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T17:11:21+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15835"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15835","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15835"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.55,0.08,0.06,0.27,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8526"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109899"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8526","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8526"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15835"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92263"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"44"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"380"},{"type":"tags","id":"2040"},{"type":"tags","id":"4974"},{"type":"tags","id":"4976"},{"type":"tags","id":"9222"},{"type":"tags","id":"9385"},{"type":"tags","id":"11633"},{"type":"tags","id":"11635"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20463"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41244"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43597"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109899","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/109899"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 62-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic for review of right carpal tunnel syndrome diagnosed three months ago. Despite workplace modifications and consistent night splinting, she reports ongoing symptoms including nocturnal paraesthesia and pain. She has a medical history of type 2 diabetes managed with metformin. She continues her office based employment as an accountant. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Neurological examination of her right hand reveals reduced sensation in the median nerve distribution, and mild thenar muscle wasting. Power is preserved in all muscle groups. The left hand examination is normal.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Surgical referral","Oral prednisolone","Gabapentin","Corticosteroid injection","Change to rigid splint"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with typical symptoms and signs of severe carpal tunnel syndrome that has failed to improve with appropriate conservative management over three months. The presence of muscle wasting indicates ongoing nerve compression. The majority of patients will improve with conservative management, but a subset will require consideration for carpal tunnel release.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESurgical referral\u003C/strong\u003E for consideration of carpal tunnel decompression is appropriate at this stage. Surgery has been shown to be more effective than conservative management for moderate to severe carpal tunnel syndrome, particularly when symptoms persist despite conservative measures. The presence of diabetes may also influence the decision for earlier surgical intervention as it can affect nerve recovery.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral prednisolone\u003C/strong\u003E is not a standard treatment for carpal tunnel syndrome. While systemic corticosteroids may temporarily reduce inflammation, they are not recommended due to potential systemic side effects and limited evidence for long-term benefit in carpal tunnel syndrome.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECorticosteroid injection\u003C/strong\u003E into the carpal tunnel can provide temporary relief but is generally considered a bridging treatment for mild or moderate carpal tunnel syndrome. Given the chronicity of symptoms and presence of muscle wasting which indicate severe disease, a more definitive solution is warranted in this case and would not be of benefit prior to surgical referral.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChange to rigid splint\u003C/strong\u003E is unlikely to provide additional benefit as the patient has already failed an appropriate trial of splinting. Continuing with the current splint while awaiting surgical assessment is reasonable.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGabapentin trial\u003C/strong\u003E may help with symptom management but does not address the underlying mechanical compression of the median nerve. It would be more appropriate for neuropathic pain without a clear mechanical cause.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ENerve conduction studies are not clinically necessary before surgical referral if clinical signs and symptoms are typical, however most hospital referral systems require a recent test before accepting a referral.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Carpal tunnel syndrome that fails to improve with conservative management after 3 months warrants consideration of surgical decompression.","Diabetes is a risk factor for carpal tunnel syndrome and may influence the success of conservative management."],"references":["Genova A, Dix O, Saefan A, Thakur M, Hassan A. Carpal Tunnel Syndrome: A Review of Literature. Cureus. 2020 Mar 19;12(3):e7333. doi: 10.7759/cureus.7333. PMID: 32313774; PMCID: PMC7164699. Available online at ; https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC7164699/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92263"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15835"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]